  "local_port": 38518,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I create date picker in Android like Google calendar?",
  "response": "To create a date picker in Android similar to the Google Calendar, you have several options. Here are a few approaches:\n\n1. Using Material DatePicker (Recommended):\n```java\n// Kotlin\nimport com.google.android.material.datepicker.MaterialDatePicker\n\nval datePicker = MaterialDatePicker.Builder.datePicker()\n    .setTitleText(\"Select Date\")\n    .setSelection(MaterialDatePicker.todayInUtcMilliseconds())\n    .build()\n\ndatePicker.show(supportFragmentManager, \"tag\")\n\ndatePicker.addOnPositiveButtonClickListener { selection ->\n    // Handle date selection\n    val selectedDate = Date(selection)\n}\n```\n\n```java\n// Java\nMaterialDatePicker datePicker = MaterialDatePicker.Builder.datePicker()\n    .setTitleText(\"Select Date\")\n    .setSelection(MaterialDatePicker.todayInUtcMilliseconds())\n    .build();\n\ndatePicker.show(getSupportFragmentManager(), \"tag\");\n\ndatePicker.addOnPositiveButtonClickListener(selection -> {\n    // Handle date selection\n    Date selectedDate = new Date(selection);\n});\n```\n\n2. Using Standard Android DatePickerDialog:\n```java\n// Kotlin\nval calendar = Calendar.getInstance()\nval year = calendar.get(Calendar.YEAR)\nval month = calendar.get(Calendar.MONTH)\nval day = calendar.get(Calendar.DAY_OF_MONTH)\n\nval datePickerDialog = DatePickerDialog(\n    this, \n    { _, selectedYear, selectedMonth, selectedDayOfMonth ->\n        // Handle date selection\n        val selectedDate = \"$selectedDayOfMonth/${selectedMonth + 1}/$selectedYear\"\n    }, \n    year, \n    month, \n    day\n)\ndatePickerDialog.show()\n```\n\n```java\n// Java\nCalendar calendar = Calendar.getInstance();\nint year = calendar.get(Calendar.YEAR);\nint month = calendar.get(Calendar.MONTH);\nint day = calendar.get(Calendar.DAY_OF_MONTH);\n\nDatePickerDialog datePickerDialog = new DatePickerDialog(\n    this, \n    (view, selectedYear, selectedMonth, selectedDayOfMonth) -> {\n        // Handle date selection\n        String selectedDate = selectedDayOfMonth + \"/\" + (selectedMonth + 1) + \"/\" + selectedYear;\n    }, \n    year, \n    month, \n    day\n);\ndatePickerDialog.show();\n```\n\n3. Custom Calendar View (More Complex):\n```xml\n<!-- activity_main.xml -->\n<CalendarView\n    android:id=\"@+id/calendarView\"\n    android:layout_width=\"match_parent\"\n    android:layout_height=\"wrap_content\"/>\n```\n\n```java\n// Java/Kotlin\nCalendarView calendarView = findViewById(R.id.calendarView);\ncalendarView.setOnDateChangeListener((view, year, month, dayOfMonth) -> {\n    // Handle date selection\n    String selectedDate = dayOfMonth + \"/\" + (month + 1) + \"/\" + year;\n});\n```\n\n4. Advanced Custom Calendar (Similar to Google Calendar):\nFor a more sophisticated calendar picker like Google Calendar, you might want to create a custom view or use a library:\n\nLibraries:\n- MaterialCalendarView\n- Android-Bootstrap Calendar\n- Material Date Range Picker\n\nExample with MaterialCalendarView:\n```groovy\n// In app's build.gradle\ndependencies {\n    implementation 'com.prolificinteractive:material-calendarview:1.4.3'\n}\n```\n\n```xml\n<!-- activity_main.xml -->\n<com.prolificinteractive.materialcalendarview.MaterialCalendarView\n    android:id=\"@+id/calendarView\"\n    android:layout_width=\"match_parent\"\n    android:layout_height=\"wrap_content\"\n    app:mcv_showOtherDates=\"all\"\n    app:mcv_selectionColor=\"@color/colorPrimary\"/>\n```\n\n```java\n// Java\nMaterialCalendarView materialCalendarView = findViewById(R.id.calendarView);\nmaterialCalendarView.setOnDateChangedListener((widget, date, selected) -> {\n    // Handle date selection\n    String selectedDate = date.getDay() + \"/\" + date.getMonth() + \"/\" + date.getYear();\n});\n```\n\nRecommended Approach:\n1. For simple date picking: Use Material DatePicker\n2. For more complex scenarios: Consider custom libraries or creating a custom view\n\nTips:\n- Add error handling\n- Consider date validation\n- Localize date formats\n- Handle different screen sizes\n\nChoose the approach that best fits your specific UI/UX requirements and app design.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
